The Effect of Fans on an NBA Game¶

Introduction¶

The NBA, or the National Basketball Association, was established in 1946. The 2021-2022 season will mark the league's 75th season. In that time, many games have been played at a variety of arenas. Over the years, it has become apparent that home-court advantage is real among many sports, especially basketball. It is possible to believe that home-court advantage can be traced back to the home team's fans that are attending the game.

In 2020, the World was hit by the COVID-19 pandemic causing many sports leagues to shut down for some time, including the NBA. When the NBA came back for the rest of the 2020 season, no fans were present at the games, but teams were playing at a neutral site. However, for the 2020-2021 NBA regular season, teams were back to playing at their home arenas, but with either no fans allowed, or limited fans allowed. So, the question becomes, what role do fans play in an NBA game? How much do they factor into the "home-court advantage" of an NBA team?

In this tutorial, I will go through the data science pipeline to show the effect that fans have on an NBA game. The goal is to collect and tidy some data from the last few NBA seasons, provide some specifics and visualize the home-court advantage with and without fans, and eventually predict the outcome of a game based on whether fans were present or not.

From this dataset, I want to get the four factors of an NBA game. These factors are 4 of the most important factors when determining the outcome of a game or even season. Much of the information can be found from this source https://www.nbastuffer.com/analytics101/four-factors/. The four factors are, effective shooting percentage, turnover percentage, offensive rebounding percentage, and free throw rate. Below are the calculations for each of these factors.

In [247]:
# All rates will be given in final as the home difference. That is, home - away.
# Effective shooting percentage
df['efg_home'] = (df['FGM_HOME'] + (.5 * df['FG3M_HOME'].astype(float))) / df['FGA_HOME'].astype(float)
df['efg_away'] = (df['FGM_AWAY'] + (.5 * df['FG3M_AWAY'].astype(float))) / df['FGA_AWAY'].astype(float)
df['efg_dif'] = (df['efg_home'] - df['efg_away']) * 100 

# Turnover percentage
df['tov_home'] = df['TOV_HOME'].astype(float) / (df['FGA_HOME'].astype(float) + (.44 * df['FTA_HOME'].astype(float)) + df['TOV_HOME'].astype(float))
df['tov_away'] = df['TOV_AWAY'].astype(float) / (df['FGA_AWAY'].astype(float) + (.44 * df['FTA_AWAY'].astype(float)) + df['TOV_AWAY'].astype(float))
df['tov_pct_dif'] = (df['tov_home'] - df['tov_away'])* 100

# Offensive rebound percentage
df['oreb_home'] = df['OREB_HOME'].astype(float) / (df['OREB_HOME'].astype(float) + df['DREB_AWAY'].astype(float))
df['oreb_away'] = df['OREB_AWAY'].astype(float) / (df['OREB_AWAY'].astype(float) + df['DREB_HOME'].astype(float))
df['oreb_pct_dif'] = (df['oreb_home'] - df['oreb_away']) * 100

# Free throw rate
df['ft_home'] = df['FTA_HOME'].astype(float) / df['FGA_HOME'].astype(float)
df['ft_away'] = df['FTA_AWAY'].astype(float) / df['FGA_AWAY'].astype(float)
df['ft_pct_dif'] = (df['ft_home'] - df['ft_away']) * 100

# Drop all columns that are no longer needed
df = df.drop(columns = ['efg_home', 'efg_away', 'tov_home', 'tov_away', 'oreb_home', 'oreb_away', 'ft_home', 'ft_away'])
df

Data Representation¶

To explore the data, I am going to want two datasets, one from the season of 2020, and one from seasons prior. These datasets will contain the attendance, and the wins and losses of the home teams and away teams from the seasons of 2009-2018 and 2020.

As we can see, the disparity between the number of home wins and losses is much smaller for the season where fans were at very limited capacity. Next, I want to see the effect that fans have on point differential when it comes to home-court advantage.

In order to truly see the effect of point differential on the fans, we will want to manipulate the data a bit. We want to get a measure of point differential across time when it comes to the home team. To do this, we will create a few variables that track the number of games in a day, the total number of home games up to a certain day, and the total home point differential up to a specific game. These variables will help visualize the home court advantage over a season plus the difference fans make in a game.

In [253]:
fans_allowed2018 = fans_allowed[fans_allowed['SEASON_ID'] == 22018]
fans_allowed2018['NUM_GAMES_DAY'] = fans_allowed2018.groupby('DAY')['DAY'].transform('count') # Count the number of games per day

# Preventing from the number of games being counted multiple times
fans_allowed2018['is_dup'] = fans_allowed2018.duplicated(subset=['DAY']) 

# Copy over the number of games in that day to later be counted
for i, c in fans_allowed2018.iterrows():
    if (fans_allowed2018.at[i, 'is_dup'] == False):
        fans_allowed2018.at[i, 'is_dup'] = c['NUM_GAMES_DAY']
# replace all the dups with 0
fans_allowed2018 = fans_allowed2018.replace(True, 0)

# Add up all games played up to this day
fans_allowed2018['TOTAL_HOME_GAMES'] = fans_allowed2018.is_dup.cumsum()
fans_allowed2018 = fans_allowed2018.drop(columns = ['is_dup'])
# Add up all pointt dif for all games
fans_allowed2018['TOTAL_PT_DIF_HOME'] = fans_allowed2018['HOME_PT_DIF'].cumsum()
# Get data from one year so it can fit into plot

The above graph shows the accumulating point differential for the home team as home games accumulate. This ultimately shows very interesting data. The red data marks that of the "COVID season" where fans were held to very limited attendance. The blue data shows a regular season where fans attend at full capacity. Based on the above graph, it would appear that fans play a very important role in terms of point differential as home point differential increases at a much greater rate over time when fans allowed. However, let's look at just how important fans are in a game by game scenario.

Based on the above linear model, it is clear that there is a relationship between attendance and home point differential as the resulting p value is 0. This is significant as we see a coefficient of .0002 for attendance. For every one fan, we see a .0002 increase in home point differential. When the fans start getting up into the 10000 and 20000, this can become a substantial difference. However, given the scatter plot and the low R-squared, it appears that there is more going on than just attendance affecting point differential., Because this is the case, it is important to look at some other factors of the game that could be impacted by the attendance, and ultimately impact the point differential.

Some important factors that can determine the outcome of a basketball game include things like shooting percentage, free throws, turnovers, and rebounds. To get a measure of this, I want to explore the effects that attendance has on the road and home team in these categories by finding the difference in terms of the home team. First, I would like to explore just how much of an effect that these factors have on a game.

When thinking about how fans may have an impact on a game, it would be important to see which factors of the game might be affected the most. Hypothesis Testing and Regression¶

To determine if there is a conclusive difference between rebounds, points, shooting percentage free throws, and turnovers when there are fans and when there are no fans, we will want to visualize the interactions that the fans have on the factors of the game. To do this, I will want to plot out each of the factors and how they effect the home point differential, but distinguish the two seasons. This will allow us to see if there are interacting terms for fans versus no fans.

To create these regression models, we will need multiple linear regression. I want to use multiple linear regression and machine learning to test and train my data as I would would like to know how strong the relationship is between the factors and home point differential. Using multiple linear regression and machine learning models can be found at this source https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2021/05/multiple-linear-regression-using-python-and-scikit-learn/. I will train and test my data to predict home point differentials which will eventually be compared to the true value.

X_train['HOME_PT_DIF'] = y_train
